     <h1>Cybersecurity Newsfeed</h1>
     <h2>üìÖ 01/12/25</h2>

     <h2>üõ°Ô∏è Vulnerabilities</h2>
     <ul>
          <li><strong>OpenPLC ScadaBR XSS Added to CISA KEV (CVE-2021-26829)</strong>: CISA added an actively exploited Cross-site Scripting (XSS) flaw in **OpenPLC ScadaBR** to its Known Exploited Vulnerabilities (KEV) Catalog. The vulnerability, which affects Windows (through v1.12.4) and Linux (through v0.9.1) via <code>system_settings.shtm</code>, is a critical risk for industrial control systems. Exploitation evidence includes a September 2025 incident where the pro-Russian group TwoNet used the flaw to deface the Human-Machine Interface (HMI) login page and disable alarms after gaining initial access. Federal agencies must remediate by December 19, 2025. <a href="https://www.cisa.gov/news-events/alerts/2025/11/28/cisa-adds-one-known-exploited-vulnerability-catalog" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

          <li><strong>Microsoft Teams Guest Access Bypass Microsoft Defender Protections</strong>: Researchers identified a cross-tenant **"blind spot"** in **Microsoft Teams' guest access**, allowing attackers to bypass **Microsoft Defender for Office 365** protections. When a user accepts a guest invitation to an external tenant, their security is governed by the hosting environment's policies, which an attacker can set to be protection-free. The attacker's initial invitation bypasses SPF/DKIM checks, and subsequently sent phishing links or malware attachments avoid the victim's Safe Links/Attachments scans. Mitigation requires restricting B2B collaboration to trusted domains and implementing cross-tenant access controls. <a href="https://thehackernews.com/2025/11/ms-teams-guest-access-can-remove.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
     </ul>

     <h2>üéØ Adversaries</h2>
     <ul>
          <li><strong>North Korea's Contagious Interview Campaign Uses 197 New NPM Packages</strong>: North Korea-linked threat actors have escalated the **Contagious Interview** supply chain attack, adding **197 new malicious npm packages** to distribute an updated **OtterCookie infostealer**. The campaign targets software developers, especially in crypto and Web3, on Windows, Linux, and macOS via social engineering (fake job interviews). The new packages, like the typosquatted <code>tailwind-magic</code>, use a postinstall script to fetch and execute the OtterCookie payload from a Vercel staging site. OtterCookie performs keylogging, clipboard theft, screenshot capture, and credential/wallet harvesting while checking for VMs. <a href="https://securityaffairs.com/185170/apt/contagious-interview-campaign-expands-with-197-npm-ppackages-spreading-new-ottercookie-malware.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

          <li><strong>Man Sentenced 7 Years for 'Evil Twin' WiFi Attacks at Airports</strong>: A 44-year-old Australian man received a **seven-year and four-month** prison sentence for running an **"evil twin" WiFi network** at airports (Perth, Melbourne, Adelaide) and during flights to steal traveler credentials. Using a **WiFi Pineapple** device, he set up rogue access points with SSIDs identical to legitimate networks, directing unsuspecting users to phishing pages to steal social media credentials. He then used the access to steal intimate images and videos from women's private accounts. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/man-behind-in-flight-evil-twin-wifi-attacks-gets-7-years-in-prison/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

          <li><strong>Adversarial Poetry Jailbreaks Frontier LLMs</strong>: A new paper details that **adversarial poetry** functions as a universal, single-turn **jailbreak technique**, circumventing safety guardrails across **25 frontier LLMs**, with some providers seeing an Attack Success Rate (ASR) over 90%. The technique reformats harmful requests into verse, using metaphor and stylistic variation to disrupt safety heuristics. Hand-crafted poems achieved an average ASR of 62%, and automated poetic conversions achieved 43% (up to 18 times higher than prose baselines), demonstrating a fundamental vulnerability in current alignment methods sensitive to linguistic style over semantic intent. <a href="https://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2025/11/prompt-injection-through-poetry.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
     </ul>

     <h2>üìà Trends</h2>
     <ul>
          <li><strong>Ransomware Payments Ban Proposed in the UK Amid 126% Surge</strong>: Ransomware incidents surged by **126%** in Q1 2025, fueling a debate over paying attackers (admitted by 41% of organizations). The **UK government** has proposed a ban on these payments, initially for public sector and **Critical National Infrastructure (CNI)** organizations, to eliminate the financial incentive for cybercriminals. The proposal aims to force organizations to prioritize robust cyber resilience, comprehensive incident response, and recovery capabilities, though experts warn it necessitates advanced security investment to prevent catastrophic business disruption. <a href="https://www.cysecurity.news/2025/11/uks-proposed-ban-on-ransomware-payments.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

          <li><strong>Threat Actors Exploit Digital Calendar Subscriptions for Phishing</strong>: Threat actors are exploiting **digital calendar subscriptions** as an overlooked attack vector, leveraging third-party server functionality to push malicious content directly to user devices. BitSight research found nearly four million devices still making daily synchronization requests to sinkholed domains. By registering expired calendar domains, attackers can serve customized **.ics files** containing phishing links, malware URLs, and scripts without user approval, bypassing traditional email filters and creating a dangerous blind spot. Users should review and remove unfamiliar calendar subscriptions and treat all calendar links as suspicious. <a href="https://www.infosecurity-magazine.com/news/threat-actors-exploit-calendar-subs/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
     </ul>

     <h2>üí• Breaches & Leaks</h2>
     <ul>
          <li><strong>Italy's FS Italiane Group Data Leaked After Almaviva IT Partner Breach</strong>: Italy's state-owned **FS Italiane Group** (national rail operator) suffered a major data exposure after a cybercriminal infiltrated the systems of its primary IT partner, **Almaviva**. The attacker published **2.3 terabytes** of allegedly stolen data on the dark web, claiming the trove includes sensitive corporate materials, contracts with public entities, HR archives, and accounting data, with documents dating to Q3 2025. Almaviva confirmed isolating the attack and notified authorities, stating critical services remained operational. <a href="https://www.cysecurity.news/2025/11/massive-data-breach-hits-italys-fs.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

          <li><strong>17,000+ Live Secrets Exposed in Public GitLab Repositories</strong>: A security engineer successfully scanned all **5.6 million public repositories on GitLab Cloud**, revealing over **17,000 verified live secrets** across more than 2,800 unique domains. This figure is nearly three times the number found in a prior Bitbucket scan. The secrets, which included API keys, passwords, and tokens, were predominantly **Google Cloud Platform (GCP)** credentials, followed by MongoDB, Telegram, and OpenAI keys. The researcher responsibly disclosed the findings and automated notifications to help affected parties revoke exposed credentials. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/public-gitlab-repositories-exposed-more-than-17-000-secrets/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

          <li><strong>French Football Federation (FFF) Discloses Data Breach</strong>: The **French Football Federation (FFF)** disclosed a data breach after attackers used a compromised account to gain unauthorized access to its administrative management software. Threat actors exfiltrated **personal and contact information** belonging to registered club members, including full names, dates of birth, addresses, phone numbers, and license numbers. The FFF immediately disabled the compromised account, forced a system-wide password reset, filed a criminal complaint, and notified relevant European authorities (ANSSI, CNIL). <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/french-football-federation-fff-discloses-data-breach-after-cyberattack/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
     </ul>

     <h2>üìö Others</h2>
     <ul>
          <li><strong>GreyNoise Launches Free IP Check Tool for Botnet/Proxy Detection</strong>: **GreyNoise Labs** launched a free tool, **GreyNoise IP Check**, allowing users to determine if their IP address has been observed as part of **malicious scanning operations** from botnets or residential proxy networks. The tool provides three results: Clean, Malicious/Suspicious (suggesting a compromised device), or Common Business Service. For suspicious results, the platform offers a 90-day historical timeline. Users with a suspicious result should run malware scans, update firmware, and change default credentials. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/greynoise-launches-free-scanner-to-check-if-youre-part-of-a-botnet/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
     </ul>

     <h2>üõ†Ô∏è Tools</h2>
     <ul>
          <li><strong>Quttera Web Malware Scanner API Adds "Evidence-as-Code" for Compliance</strong>: Quttera launched a major update to its Web Malware Scanner API, introducing **"Evidence-as-Code"** to automate security compliance for standards like **SOC 2 and PCI DSS v4.0**. The new capability transforms malware detection into real-time, structured JSON data with embedded compliance metadata, eliminating the manual collection of evidence for audits. It specifically targets PCI DSS v4.0 requirements, such as detecting unauthorized changes to payment scripts, and includes an AI-powered Threat Encyclopedia for context and remediation guidance. <a href="https://hackread.com/quttera-evidence-as-code-api-soc-pci-dss/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
     </ul>

